# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-series-databases-obs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In information theory, **data compression**, **source coding**, or **bit-rate reduction** is the process of encoding information using fewer bits than the original representation.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Any particular compression is either lossy or lossless.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossless compression reduces bits by identifying and eliminating statistical redundancy.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] No information is lost in lossless compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy compression reduces bits by removing unnecessary or less important information.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Typically, a device that performs data compression is referred to as an encoder, and one that performs the reversal of the process (decompression) as a decoder.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The process of reducing the size of a data file is often referred to as data compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the context of data transmission, it is called source coding: encoding is done at the source of the data before it is stored or transmitted.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Source coding should not be confused with channel coding, for error detection and correction or line coding, the means for mapping data onto a signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Data compression algorithms present a space–time complexity trade-off between the bytes needed to store or transmit information, and the computational resources needed to perform the encoding and decoding.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The design of data compression schemes involves balancing the degree of compression, the amount of distortion introduced (when using lossy data compression), and the computational resources or time required to compress and decompress the data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms usually exploit statistical redundancy to represent data without losing any information, so that the process is reversible.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossless compression is possible because most real-world data exhibits statistical redundancy.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For example, an image may have areas of color that do not change over several pixels; instead of coding "red pixel, red pixel, ..." the data may be encoded as "279 red pixels".
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This is a basic example of run-length encoding; there are many schemes to reduce file size by eliminating redundancy.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The Lempel–Ziv (LZ) compression methods are among the most popular algorithms for lossless storage.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] DEFLATE is a variation on LZ optimized for decompression speed and compression ratio, but compression can be slow.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the mid-1980s, following work by Terry Welch, the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) algorithm rapidly became the method of choice for most general-purpose compression systems.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] LZW is used in GIF images, programs such as PKZIP, and hardware devices such as modems.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] LZ methods use a table-based compression model where table entries are substituted for repeated strings of data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For most LZ methods, this table is generated dynamically from earlier data in the input.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The table itself is often Huffman encoded.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Grammar-based codes like this can compress highly repetitive input extremely effectively, for instance, a biological data collection of the same or closely related species, a huge versioned document collection, internet archival, etc.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The basic task of grammar-based codes is constructing a context-free grammar deriving a single string.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Other practical grammar compression algorithms include Sequitur and Re-Pair.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The strongest modern lossless compressors use probabilistic models, such as prediction by partial matching.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The Burrows–Wheeler transform can also be viewed as an indirect form of statistical modelling.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In a further refinement of the direct use of probabilistic modelling, statistical estimates can be coupled to an algorithm called arithmetic coding.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Arithmetic coding is a more modern coding technique that uses the mathematical calculations of a finite-state machine to produce a string of encoded bits from a series of input data symbols.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It can achieve superior compression compared to other techniques, such as the better-known Huffman algorithm.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It uses an internal memory state to avoid the need to perform a one-to-one mapping of individual input symbols to distinct representations that use an integer number of bits, and it clears out the internal memory only after encoding the entire string of data symbols.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Arithmetic coding applies especially well to adaptive data compression tasks where the statistics vary and are context-dependent, as it can be easily coupled with an adaptive model of the probability distribution of the input data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] An early example of the use of arithmetic coding was in an optional (but not widely used) feature of the JPEG image coding standard.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It has since been applied in various other designs including H.263, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC for video coding.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Archive software typically has the ability to adjust the "dictionary size", where a larger size demands more random-access memory during compression and decompression, but compresses more strongly, especially on repeating patterns in files' content.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the late 1980s, digital images became more common, and standards for lossless image compression emerged.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the early 1990s, lossy compression methods began to be widely used.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In these schemes, some loss of information is accepted as dropping nonessential detail can save storage space.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] There is a corresponding trade-off between preserving information and reducing size.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy data compression schemes are designed based on research on how people perceive the data in question.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For example, the human eye is more sensitive to subtle variations in luminance than it is to the variations in color.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] JPEG image compression works in part by rounding off nonessential bits of information.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] A number of popular compression formats exploit these perceptual differences, including psychoacoustics for sound, and psychovisuals for images and video.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Most forms of lossy compression are based on transform coding, especially the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It was first proposed in 1972 by Nasir Ahmed, who then developed a working algorithm with T.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Rao in 1973, before introducing it in January 1974.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] DCT is the most widely used lossy compression method, and is used in multimedia formats for images (such as JPEG and HEIF), video (such as MPEG, AVC and HEVC) and audio (such as MP3, AAC and Vorbis).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy image compression is used in digital cameras, to increase storage capacities.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Similarly, DVDs, Blu-ray and streaming video use lossy video coding formats.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy compression is extensively used in video.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In lossy audio compression, methods of psychoacoustics are used to remove non-audible (or less audible) components of the audio signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Compression of human speech is often performed with even more specialized techniques; speech coding is distinguished as a separate discipline from general-purpose audio compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Speech coding is used in internet telephony, for example, audio compression is used for CD ripping and is decoded by the audio players.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy compression can cause generation loss.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The theoretical basis for compression is provided by information theory and, more specifically, Shannon's source coding theorem; domain-specific theories include algorithmic information theory for lossless compression and rate–distortion theory for lossy compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] These areas of study were essentially created by Claude Shannon, who published fundamental papers on the topic in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Other topics associated with compression include coding theory and statistical inference.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Data compression can be viewed as a special case of data differencing.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This is the same as considering absolute entropy (corresponding to data compression) as a special case of relative entropy (corresponding to data differencing) with no initial data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The term *differential compression* is used to emphasize the data differencing connection.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Entropy coding originated in the 1940s with the introduction of Shannon–Fano coding, the basis for Huffman coding which was developed in 1950.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Transform coding dates back to the late 1960s, with the introduction of fast Fourier transform (FFT) coding in 1968 and the Hadamard transform in 1969.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] An important image compression technique is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a technique developed in the early 1970s.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] DCT is the basis for JPEG, a lossy compression format which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) in 1992.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] JPEG greatly reduces the amount of data required to represent an image at the cost of a relatively small reduction in image quality and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Its highly efficient DCT-based compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) is a lossless compression algorithm developed in 1984.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It is used in the GIF format, introduced in 1987.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] DEFLATE, a lossless compression algorithm specified in 1996, is used in the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Wavelet compression, the use of wavelets in image compression, began after the development of DCT coding.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The JPEG 2000 standard was introduced in 2000.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Audio data compression, not to be confused with dynamic range compression, has the potential to reduce the transmission bandwidth and storage requirements of audio data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Audio compression formats compression algorithms are implemented in software as audio codecs.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In both lossy and lossless compression, information redundancy is reduced, using methods such as coding, quantization, DCT and linear prediction to reduce the amount of information used to represent the uncompressed data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy audio compression algorithms provide higher compression and are used in numerous audio applications including Vorbis and MP3.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] These algorithms almost all rely on psychoacoustics to eliminate or reduce fidelity of less audible sounds, thereby reducing the space required to store or transmit them.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The acceptable trade-off between loss of audio quality and transmission or storage size depends upon the application.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For example, one 640 MB compact disc (CD) holds approximately one hour of uncompressed high fidelity music, less than 2 hours of music compressed losslessly, or 7 hours of music compressed in the MP3 format at a medium bit rate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] A digital sound recorder can typically store around 200 hours of clearly intelligible speech in 640 MB.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossless audio compression produces a representation of digital data that can be decoded to an exact digital duplicate of the original.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Compression ratios are around 50–60% of the original size, which is similar to those for generic lossless data compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossless codecs use curve fitting or linear prediction as a basis for estimating the signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Parameters describing the estimation and the difference between the estimation and the actual signal are coded separately.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] A number of lossless audio compression formats exist.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] See list of lossless codecs for a listing.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Some formats are associated with a distinct system, such as Direct Stream Transfer, used in Super Audio CD and Meridian Lossless Packing, used in DVD-Audio, Dolby TrueHD, Blu-ray and HD DVD.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Some audio file formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction; this allows stripping the correction to easily obtain a lossy file.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, and OptimFROG DualStream.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] When audio files are to be processed, either by further compression or for editing, it is desirable to work from an unchanged original (uncompressed or losslessly compressed).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Processing of a lossily compressed file for some purpose usually produces a final result inferior to the creation of the same compressed file from an uncompressed original.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In addition to sound editing or mixing, lossless audio compression is often used for archival storage, or as master copies.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy audio compression is used in a wide range of applications.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In addition to standalone audio-only applications of file playback in MP3 players or computers, digitally compressed audio streams are used in most video DVDs, digital television, streaming media on the Internet, satellite and cable radio, and increasingly in terrestrial radio broadcasts.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy compression typically achieves far greater compression than lossless compression, by discarding less-critical data based on psychoacoustic optimizations.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Psychoacoustics recognizes that not all data in an audio stream can be perceived by the human auditory system.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Most lossy compression reduces redundancy by first identifying perceptually irrelevant sounds, that is, sounds that are very hard to hear.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Typical examples include high frequencies or sounds that occur at the same time as louder sounds.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Those irrelevant sounds are coded with decreased accuracy or not at all.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Due to the nature of lossy algorithms, audio quality suffers a digital generation loss when a file is decompressed and recompressed.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This makes lossy compression unsuitable for storing the intermediate results in professional audio engineering applications, such as sound editing and multitrack recording.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] However, lossy formats such as MP3 are very popular with end-users as the file size is reduced to 5-20% of the original size and a megabyte can store about a minute's worth of music at adequate quality.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Several proprietary lossy compression algorithms have been developed that provide higher quality audio performance by using a combination of lossless and lossy algorithms with adaptive bit rates and lower compression ratios.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Examples include aptX, LDAC, LHDC, MQA and SCL6.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] To determine what information in an audio signal is perceptually irrelevant, most lossy compression algorithms use transforms such as the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) to convert time domain sampled waveforms into a transform domain, typically the frequency domain.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Once transformed, component frequencies can be prioritized according to how audible they are.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Equal-loudness contours may also be used to weigh the perceptual importance of components.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Models of the human ear-brain combination incorporating such effects are often called psychoacoustic models.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Other types of lossy compressors, such as the linear predictive coding (LPC) used with speech, are source-based coders.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] LPC uses a model of the human vocal tract to analyze speech sounds and infer the parameters used by the model to produce them moment to moment.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] These changing parameters are transmitted or stored and used to drive another model in the decoder, which reproduces the sound.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Lossy formats are often used for the distribution of streaming audio or interactive communication (such as in cell phone networks).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In such applications, the data must be decompressed as the data flows, rather than after the entire data stream has been transmitted.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Not all audio codecs can be used for streaming applications.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Latency is introduced by the methods used to encode and decode the data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Some codecs will analyze a longer segment, called a *frame*, of the data to optimize efficiency, and then code it in a manner that requires a larger segment of data at one time to decode.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The inherent latency of the coding algorithm can be critical; for example, when there is a two-way transmission of data, such as with a telephone conversation, significant delays may seriously degrade the perceived quality.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In contrast to the speed of compression, which is proportional to the number of operations required by the algorithm, here latency refers to the number of samples that must be analyzed before a block of audio is processed.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the minimum case, latency is zero samples (e.g., if the coder/decoder simply reduces the number of bits used to quantize the signal).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Time domain algorithms such as LPC also often have low latencies, hence their popularity in speech coding for telephony.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In algorithms such as MP3, however, a large number of samples have to be analyzed to implement a psychoacoustic model in the frequency domain, and latency is on the order of 23 ms.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Speech encoding is an important category of audio data compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The perceptual models used to estimate what aspects of speech a human ear can hear are generally somewhat different from those used for music.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The range of frequencies needed to convey the sounds of a human voice is normally far narrower than that needed for music, and the sound is normally less complex.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] As a result, speech can be encoded at high quality using a relatively low bit rate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The earliest algorithms used in speech encoding (and audio data compression in general) were the A-law algorithm and the μ-law algorithm.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Early audio research was conducted at Bell Labs.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Chapin Cutler filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In 1973, Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Perceptual coding is used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3 and AAC.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Discrete cosine transform (DCT), developed by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Rao in 1974, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3, Dolby Digital, and AAC.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The world's first commercial broadcast automation audio compression system was developed by Oscar Bonello, an engineering professor at the University of Buenos Aires.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This broadcast automation system was launched in 1987 under the name Audicom.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] A literature compendium for a large variety of audio coding systems was published in the IEEE's *Journal on Selected Areas in Communications* (*JSAC*), in February 1988.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] While there were some papers from before that time, this collection documented an entire variety of finished, working audio coders, nearly all of them using perceptual techniques and some kind of frequency analysis and back-end noiseless coding.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Uncompressed video requires a very high data rate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Although lossless video compression codecs perform at a compression factor of 5 to 12, a typical H.264 lossy compression video has a compression factor between 20 and 200.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards are the DCT and motion compensation (MC).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT video coding (block motion compensation).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Most video codecs are used alongside audio compression techniques to store the separate but complementary data streams as one combined package using so-called *container formats*.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Video data may be represented as a series of still image frames.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Such data usually contains abundant amounts of spatial and temporal redundancy.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Video compression algorithms attempt to reduce redundancy and store information more compactly.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Most video compression formats and codecs exploit both spatial and temporal redundancy (e.g., through difference coding with motion compensation).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Similarities can be encoded by only storing differences between e.g., temporally adjacent frames (inter-frame coding) or spatially adjacent pixels (intra-frame coding).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Inter-frame compression (a temporal delta encoding) (re)uses data from one or more earlier or later frames in a sequence to describe the current frame.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Intra-frame coding, on the other hand, uses only data from within the current frame, effectively being still-image compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The intra-frame video coding formats used in camcorders and video editing employ simpler compression that uses only intra-frame prediction.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This simplifies video editing software, as it prevents a situation in which a compressed frame refers to data that the editor has deleted.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Usually, video compression additionally employs lossy compression techniques like quantization that reduce aspects of the source data that are (more or less) irrelevant to the human visual perception by exploiting perceptual features of human vision.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For example, small differences in color are more difficult to perceive than are changes in brightness.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Compression algorithms can average a color across these similar areas in a manner similar to those used in JPEG image compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] As in all lossy compression, there is a trade-off between video quality and bit rate, cost of processing the compression and decompression, and system requirements.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Highly compressed video may present visible or distracting artifacts.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Other methods other than the prevalent DCT-based transform formats, such as fractal compression, matching pursuit and the use of a discrete wavelet transform (DWT), have been the subject of some research, but are typically not used in practical products.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Wavelet compression is used in still-image coders and video coders without motion compensation.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Interest in fractal compression seems to be waning, due to recent theoretical analysis showing a comparative lack of effectiveness of such methods.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In inter-frame coding, individual frames of a video sequence are compared from one frame to the next, and the video compression codec records the differences to the reference frame.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] If the frame contains areas where nothing has moved, the system can simply issue a short command that copies that part of the previous frame into the next one.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] If sections of the frame move in a simple manner, the compressor can emit a (slightly longer) command that tells the decompressor to shift, rotate, lighten, or darken the copy.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] This longer command still remains much shorter than data generated by intra-frame compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Usually, the encoder will also transmit a residue signal which describes the remaining, more subtle differences to the reference imagery.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Using entropy coding, these residue signals have a more compact representation than the full signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In areas of video with more motion, the compression must encode more data to keep up with the larger number of pixels that are changing.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Commonly, the high-frequency detail of explosions, flames, flocks of animals, and some panning shots will lead to decreases in quality or increases in the variable bitrate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Many commonly used video compression methods (e.g., those in standards approved by the ITU-T or ISO) share the same basic architecture that dates back to H.261, which was standardized in 1988 by the ITU-T.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] They mostly rely on the DCT, applied to rectangular blocks of neighboring pixels, and temporal prediction using motion vectors, as well as nowadays also an in-loop filtering step.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the prediction stage, various deduplication and difference-coding techniques are applied that help decorrelate data and describe new data based on already transmitted data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Then, rectangular blocks of remaining pixel data are transformed to the frequency domain.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the main lossy processing stage, frequency domain data gets quantized in order to reduce information that is irrelevant to human visual perception.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In the last stage, statistical redundancy gets largely eliminated by an entropy coder, which often applies some form of arithmetic coding.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In an additional in-loop filtering stage, various filters can be applied to the reconstructed image signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] By computing these filters also inside the encoding loop, they can help compression because they can be applied to reference material before it gets used in the prediction process and they can be guided using the original signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The most popular example are deblocking filters that blur out blocking artifacts from quantization discontinuities at transform block boundaries.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Cherry proposed a run-length encoding bandwidth compression scheme for the transmission of analog television signals.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The DCT, which is fundamental to modern video compression, was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] H.261, which debuted in 1988, commercially introduced the prevalent basic architecture of video compression technology.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It was the first video coding format based on DCT compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] H.261 was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT and Toshiba.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It was also developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] H.264/MPEG-4 AVC was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] AVC commercially introduced the modern context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) and context-adaptive variable-length coding (CAVLC) algorithms.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Genetics compression algorithms are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and genetic algorithms adapted to the specific datatype.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published a genetic compression algorithm that does not use a reference genome for compression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression and is less computationally intensive than the leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] For this, Chanda, Elhaik, and Bader introduced MAF-based encoding (MAFE), which reduces the heterogeneity of the dataset by sorting SNPs by their minor allele frequency, thus homogenizing the dataset.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] Other algorithms developed in 2009 and 2013 (DNAZip and GenomeZip) have compression ratios of up to 1200-fold—allowing 6 billion basepair diploid human genomes to be stored in 2.5 megabytes (relative to a reference genome or averaged over many genomes).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It is estimated that the total amount of data that is stored on the world's storage devices could be further compressed with existing compression algorithms by a remaining average factor of 4.5:1.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/data-compression] It is estimated that the combined technological capacity of the world to store information provides 1,300 exabytes of hardware digits in 2007, but when the corresponding content is optimally compressed, this only represents 295 exabytes of Shannon information.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Write data to InfluxDB using a number of different options.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Use Flux to query and transform your data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Use InfluxDB tasks to process and downsample data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Build powerful dashboards to visualize your data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Monitor metrics and send alerts with InfluxDB.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Customize your **InfluxDB OSS URL** and we’ll update code examples for you.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] For more information, see InfluxDB OSS URLs.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Stronger token security in **InfluxDB OSS 2.9.0** — tokens are hashed on disk by default.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Existing tokens are hashed on first startup and can’t be recovered afterward.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Hashed tokens authenticate exactly like unhashed tokens — clients and integrations keep working.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Explorer 1.9 is now available with InfluxQL support, an AI-assisted Flux to SQL converter (beta), and new live sample data simulators.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Explorer 1.9 includes new features and improvements that make it easier to query, visualize, and manage data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] InfluxDB 3 Core 3.10 adds an automatic catalog format upgrade, a configurable query-concurrency limit, and processing engine improvements.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] For more information, see the InfluxDB 3 Core release notes.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] InfluxDB 3 Enterprise 3.10 adds automated backup and restore, row-level deletions, and user management, with an automatic catalog format upgrade and performance preview improvements.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Backup and restore, row-level deletions, and the performance preview require the Enterprise storage engine upgrade (opt-in beta).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Telegraf Enterprise combines Telegraf Controller, a centralized management console for Telegraf, with official support from InfluxData.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] Manage configurations, monitor fleet health, and operate tens of thousands of Telegraf agents from a single system.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] tag for InfluxDB Docker images will point to InfluxDB 3 Core.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] To avoid unexpected upgrades, use specific version tags in your Docker deployments.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb-v2] If using Docker to install and run InfluxDB, the `latest` tag will point to InfluxDB 3 Core.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] The latest version of InfluxDB, 3.x, is written in the Rust programming language.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Y Combinator-backed company Errplane began developing InfluxDB as an open-source project in late 2013 for performance monitoring and alerting.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Errplane raised an $8.1M Series A financing led by Mayfield Fund and Trinity Ventures in November 2014.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] In late 2015, Errplane officially changed its name to InfluxData Inc.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] InfluxData raised Series B round of funding of $16 million in September 2016.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] In February 2018, InfluxData closed a $35 million Series C round of funding led by Sapphire Ventures.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Another round of $60 million was disclosed in 2019.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] In February 2023, another $81 million was closed in a Series E round.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] InfluxDB provides an SQL-like language with built-in time-centric functions for querying a data structure composed of measurements, series, and points.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Each point consists of several key-value pairs called the fieldset and a timestamp.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] When grouped together by a set of key-value pairs called the tagset, these define a series.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Finally, series are grouped together by a string identifier to form a measurement.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Values can be 64-bit integers, 64-bit floating points, strings, and booleans.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Points are indexed by their time and tagset.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Retention policies are defined on a measurement and control how data is downsampled and deleted.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Continuous Queries run periodically, storing results in a target measurement.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] InfluxData regularly hosts events related to InfluxDB called InfluxDays.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] The InfluxDays are technical conventions focused on the evolution of InfluxDB on technical and business points of view.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Those events take place once a year in three locations: New York, San Francisco or London.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] The InfluxDays cover a wide variety of different subjects: software engineering and coding talks as well as business-focused and practical workshops.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Companies can showcase how they use InfluxDB.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] InfluxDB accepts data via HTTP, TCP, and UDP.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] measurement(,tag_key=tag_val)* field_key=field_val(,field_key_n=field_value_n)* (nanoseconds-timestamp)?
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Contributors to InfluxDB need to give InfluxData Inc. the right to license the contributions and the rest of the software in any way, including under a closed-source license.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] The Contributor License Agreement claims not to be a copyright transfer agreement.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] In May 2016, InfluxData announced that the computer cluster component of InfluxDB would be sold as closed-source software in order to create a sustainable source of funding for the project's development.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Community reaction was mixed, with some feeling the move was a "bait and switch".
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] InfluxDB 3 Core is InfluxData's newest open source product and is intentionally designed to be an “edge data collector”, not a replacement for InfluxDB OSS v1 and v2.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] InfluxDB 3 Core has a 5 database limit and does not include a data compactor for fast historical querying.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] In addition to InfluxDB 3 Core, InfluxDB 3 Enterprise is the commercial version of the open source core project.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/influxdb] Purchasing a software license for InfluxDB 3 Enterprise is required to replace InfluxDB OSS v1 and v2 functionality in a commercial setting, though a free version of InfluxDB 3 Enterprise is available for hobbyist and home use.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Prometheus includes a local on-disk time series database, but also optionally integrates with remote storage systems.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Prometheus's local time series database stores data in a custom, highly efficient format on local storage.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Ingested samples are grouped into two-hour blocks.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Each block consists of a directory that contains a chunks subdirectory with all the time series samples for that time window, a metadata file, and an index file (which maps metric names and labels to the time series in the chunks directory).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The samples in the chunks directory are organized into one or more segment files, each up to 512 MB by default.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] When series are deleted via the API, the deletion records are stored in separate tombstone files rather than being immediately removed from the chunk segments.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The current block for incoming samples is kept in memory and is not fully persisted.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] It is secured against crashes by a write-ahead log (WAL) that can be replayed when the Prometheus server restarts.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Write-ahead log files are stored in the `wal` directory in 128MB segments.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] These files contain raw data that has not yet been compacted; thus they are significantly larger than regular block files.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Prometheus will retain a minimum of three write-ahead log files.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] High-traffic servers may retain more than three WAL files in order to keep at least two hours of raw data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Note that a limitation of local storage is that it is not clustered or replicated.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Thus, it is not arbitrarily scalable or durable in the face of drive or node outages and should be managed like any other single node database.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] With proper architecture, it is possible to retain years of data in local storage.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Backups made without snapshots run the risk of losing data that was recorded since the last TSDB block was created, which typically happens every two hours, covering the last three hours of samples.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Excluding the WAL files (the `chunks_head/`, `wal/`, and `wbl/` directories in `storage.tsdb.path`) on backup or restore will ensure a coherent backup, in any case, at the cost of losing the time range covered by the WAL files.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Alternatively, external storage may be used via the remote read/write APIs.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Careful evaluation is required for these systems as they vary greatly in durability, performance, and efficiency.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] For further details on file format, see TSDB format .
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The initial two-hour blocks are eventually compacted into longer blocks in the background.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Compaction will create larger blocks containing data spanning up to 10% of the retention time, or 31 days, whichever is smaller.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Prometheus has several flags that configure local storage.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Prometheus stores an average of only 1-2 bytes per sample.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] To lower the rate of ingested samples, you can either reduce the number of time series you scrape (fewer targets or fewer series per target), or you can increase the scrape interval.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] However, reducing the number of series is likely more effective, due to compression of samples within a series.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] If your local storage becomes corrupted to the point where Prometheus will not start it is recommended to backup the storage directory and restore the corrupted block directories from your backups.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] If you do not have backups the last resort is to remove the corrupted files.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] For example you can try removing individual block directories or the write-ahead-log (WAL) files.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Note that this means losing the data for the time range those blocks or WAL covers.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] If both time and size retention policies are specified, whichever triggers first will be used.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Expired block cleanup happens in the background.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] It may take up to two hours to remove expired blocks.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Blocks must be fully expired before they are removed.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] If you are utilizing `storage.tsdb.retention.size` to set a size limit, you will want to consider the right size for this value relative to the storage you have allocated for Prometheus.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] It is wise to reduce the retention size to provide a buffer, ensuring that older entries will be removed before the allocated storage for Prometheus becomes full.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] At present, we recommend setting the retention size to, at most, 80-85% of your allocated Prometheus disk space.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] This increases the likelihood that older entries will be removed prior to hitting any disk limitations.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Prometheus's local storage is limited to a single node's scalability and durability.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Instead of trying to solve clustered storage in Prometheus itself, Prometheus offers a set of interfaces that allow integrating with remote storage systems.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The remote read and write protocols both use a snappy-compressed protocol buffer encoding over HTTP.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The read protocol is not yet considered as stable API.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The write protocol has a stable specification for 1.0 version and experimental specification for 2.0 version, both supported by Prometheus server.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] For details on configuring remote storage integrations in Prometheus as a client, see the remote write and remote read sections of the Prometheus configuration documentation.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Note that on the read path, Prometheus only fetches raw series data for a set of label selectors and time ranges from the remote end.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] All PromQL evaluation on the raw data still happens in Prometheus itself.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] This means that remote read queries have some scalability limit, since all necessary data needs to be loaded into the querying Prometheus server first and then processed there.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] However, supporting fully distributed evaluation of PromQL was deemed infeasible for the time being.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The built-in remote write receiver can be enabled by setting the `--web.enable-remote-write-receiver` command line flag.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] When enabled, the remote write receiver endpoint is `/api/v1/write`.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The remote read endpoint is available on `/api/v1/read`.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] To learn more about existing integrations with remote storage systems, see the Integrations documentation.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] If a user wants to create blocks into the TSDB from data that is in OpenMetrics format, they can do so using backfilling.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] However, they should be careful and note that it is not safe to backfill data from the last 3 hours (the current head block) as this time range may overlap with the current head block Prometheus is still mutating.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Backfilling will create new TSDB blocks, each containing two hours of metrics data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] This limits the memory requirements of block creation.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Compacting the two hour blocks into larger blocks is later done by the Prometheus server itself.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] A typical use case is to migrate metrics data from a different monitoring system or time-series database to Prometheus.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] To do so, the user must first convert the source data into OpenMetrics format, which is the input format for the backfilling as described below.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Note that native histograms and staleness markers are not supported by this procedure, as they cannot be represented in the OpenMetrics format.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Backfilling can be used via the `promtool` command line.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] `promtool` will write the blocks to a directory.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] By default this output directory is ./data/, you can change it by using the name of the desired output directory as an optional argument in the sub-command.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] After the creation of the blocks, move it to the data directory of Prometheus.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] If there is an overlap with the existing blocks in Prometheus, the flag `--storage.tsdb.allow-overlapping-blocks` needs to be set for Prometheus versions v2.38 and below.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Note that any backfilled data is subject to the retention configured for your Prometheus server (by time or size).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] By default, the promtool will use the default block duration (2h) for the blocks; this behavior is the most generally applicable and correct.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] However, when backfilling data over a long range of times, it may be advantageous to use a larger value for the block duration to backfill faster and prevent additional compactions by TSDB later.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The `--max-block-duration` flag allows the user to configure a maximum duration of blocks.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The backfilling tool will pick a suitable block duration no larger than this.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] While larger blocks may improve the performance of backfilling large datasets, drawbacks exist as well.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Time-based retention policies must keep the entire block around if even one sample of the (potentially large) block is still within the retention policy.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Conversely, size-based retention policies will remove the entire block even if the TSDB only goes over the size limit in a minor way.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Therefore, backfilling with few blocks, thereby choosing a larger block duration, must be done with care and is not recommended for any production instances.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] When a new recording rule is created, there is no historical data for it.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Recording rule data only exists from the creation time on.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] `promtool` makes it possible to create historical recording rule data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] To see all options, use: `$ promtool tsdb create-blocks-from rules --help`.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The recording rule files provided should be a normal Prometheus rules file.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] The output of `promtool tsdb create-blocks-from rules` command is a directory that contains blocks with the historical rule data for all rules in the recording rule files.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] By default, the output directory is `data/`.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] In order to make use of this new block data, the blocks must be moved to a running Prometheus instance data dir `storage.tsdb.path` (for Prometheus versions v2.38 and below, the flag `--storage.tsdb.allow-overlapping-blocks` must be enabled).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/latest-storage] Once moved, the new blocks will merge with existing blocks when the next compaction runs.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] It also includes tools to extract round-robin data in a graphical format, for which it was originally intended.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] Bindings exist for several programming languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, Tcl, PHP and Lua.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] There is an independent full Java implementation called rrd4j.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] RRDtool assumes time-variable data in intervals of a certain length.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] This interval, usually named the **step**, is specified upon creation of an RRD file and cannot be changed afterwards.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] Because data may not always be available at just the right time, RRDtool will automatically interpolate any submitted data to fit its internal time steps.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] The value for a specific step, after interpolation, is named a primary data point (**PDP**).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] Multiple PDPs may be consolidated according to a consolidation function (**CF**) to form a consolidated data point (**CDP**).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] Typical consolidation functions are average, minimum, and maximum.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] After the data has been consolidated, the resulting CDP is stored in a round-robin archive (**RRA**).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] A round-robin archive stores a fixed number of CDPs and specifies how many PDPs should be consolidated into one CDP and which CF to use.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] After this time the archive will "wrap around": the next insertion will overwrite the oldest entry.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] This behavior is referred to as "round-robin" and is the reason for the program's name.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] To cover several timespans and/or use several consolidation functions, an RRD file may contain multiple RRAs.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] The data retrieval function of RRDtool automatically selects the archive with the highest resolution that still covers the requested timespan.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] This mechanism is also used by RRDtool's graphing subsystem.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/rrdtool] The following table contains the **release history of RRDtool**, showing its major releases.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:time-series-databases-obs/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
